---
import DocsLayout from '../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';

const title = 'Tailwind vs LSCSS';
const description = 'Compare Tailwind CSS and Layered Semantic CSS for maintainability, speed, naming, reuse, design systems, and long-term front-end architecture.';
---

<DocsLayout
    title={title}
    description={description}
>
    <article>
        <p class="eyebrow">Comparison</p>

        <h1>
            Tailwind vs LSCSS
        </h1>

        <p>
            Tailwind solves speed and consistency by pushing styling decisions
            directly into HTML. LSCSS solves maintainability by keeping styling
            architecture in CSS where it belongs.
        </p>

        <p>
            Both approaches try to reduce chaos. They simply choose different
            battlefields.
        </p>

        <h2>
            Main differences
        </h2>

        <ul>
            <li>Tailwind uses utility classes directly in markup</li>
            <li>LSCSS uses semantic component names and layered CSS</li>
            <li>Tailwind reduces custom CSS writing</li>
            <li>LSCSS reduces HTML noise and preserves clearer structure</li>
            <li>Tailwind relies heavily on utility composition</li>
            <li>LSCSS prefers explicit components, modifiers, and state classes</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>
            Where Tailwind works well
        </h2>

        <ul>
            <li>fast product delivery with small teams</li>
            <li>design systems with strict tokens and constraints</li>
            <li>applications where utility speed matters more than semantic markup</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>
            Where LSCSS helps more
        </h2>

        <ul>
            <li>content-heavy websites and long-lived platforms</li>
            <li>teams prioritising readable HTML and maintainable CSS</li>
            <li>projects with strong accessibility and progressive enhancement goals</li>
            <li>systems where component architecture matters more than rapid utility composition</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>
            Recommended reading
        </h2>

        <ul>
            <li><a href="/principles/">Core principles</a></li>
            <li><a href="/utilities/">Utilities</a></li>
            <li><a href="/theme-layer/">Theme layer</a></li>
            <li><a href="/guides/performance-and-css/">Performance and CSS</a></li>
        </ul>

        <p>
            Tailwind is fast. LSCSS is calm. Choose based on the project, not
            because somebody on the internet called one of them dead.
        </p>
    </article>
</DocsLayout>
